1976: Carter beat Ford, a (partial) one term president
1980: Reagan beat Carter, a one term president
1992: Clinton beat Bush, a one term president
2020: Alleged victory of Biden over Trump, a one term president

What I am saying is that NO ONE in this country actually knows with any degree of certainty that their vote--as they actually voted--was tabulated into the totals that we are regularly seeing on our computer and TV screens. The voter systems and  processes (including the voter software!) we used in the various states in this country are certainly NOT foolproof or beyond hacking--especially if the hacking is happening from insiders to the software development itself. In addition, the DOJ should investigate how these particular software companies won the contracts they did in order to be employed in this year's election, and what kinds of nefarious connections there might be between those software company executives and those responsible for making the decisions as to which software was to be used on a state-by-state basis. For one, during a once-in-a-century-pandemic, many state governments, including Georgia, which has a Trump-supporting Governor, Secretary of State, and Elections Commissioner, expanded no-excuse mail-in voting. In fact, it was the Republican state legislatures in Wisconsin and Pennsylvania who passed laws forbidding precincts from tabulating mail-in votes until polls closed on election day, which substantially delayed the process and made it appear that Trump had leads in those states because election-day votes were counted first. The reason Biden appeared to make a sudden comeback is that Democrats disproportionately voted by mail, rather than in person, because Trump explicitly told Republicans to vote in-person and mail-in ballots were counted late in those rust belt states. Conversely, in Arizona, the Republican state legislature allowed precincts to start counting mail-in ballots before election day, which is why Biden appeared to have a much bigger lead that Trump began to make up. As such, by your logic, there was fraud in Trump's favor in Arizona because Biden's big lead shrunk over time. In my county in Michigan the county clerk claims there are approximately 131,000 registered voters on the rolls.  According to the recent census, the population of the county that is age 18 or older, and thus eligible to vote (but not necessarily registered), is roughly 119,000.  So if 100% of the county's voter-eligible population were registered to vote, we could only have a max of 119,000 registered voters.  In Michigan the statewide average for registered voters as a percentage of eligible voters is roughly 74%.  So even if my county were above average at getting eligible voters registered and hit 80%, there would still only be about 95,000 registered voters...far cry from 131,000.  Therefore it seems logical to conclude that the voter rolls in my county are far from accurate, and therefore ripe for voter fraud via mail-in ballots.  My mostly rural county makes up roughly 1.5% of the population of Michigan, so if you extrapolate that across the state, the potential for mass voter fraud is enormous...especially in the 5 largest counties (Metro Detroit area, Grand Rapids, and Flint) which comprise 49.5% of the states population.  Imagine how inaccurate the voter rolls could be in these 5 mostly Democrat counties that comprise 5 million people...truly scary the fraud that could be perpetrated.
